pment as social justice educator/scholars in the face of colonizing forces. Using a rhizomatic approach, the editors' meta-analysis identifies patterns of similarity and differences and theorizes about the exercise of agency in resistance and identity formation. In our increasingly diverse society, Becoming Critical is a wonderful resource for teacher education and sociology of education as it presents an alternative methodological approach for qualitative inquiry. The book contributes to students' understanding of the development of critical theories—especially as they pertain to identities. The contributors make use of the work of critical scholars such as Collins, hooks, Weber, Foucault, and others relevant to the lives of students and educators today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCritical pedagogy. 0aMinorities in higher educationxBiographyxUnited States. 0aMinorities in higher educationxUnited States. 0aMinorities in higher educationzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aMinorities in higher educationzUnited States. 0aSocial justicexStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aTeachersxTraining ofxSocial aspectsxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxBiography. 0aTeachersxTraining ofxSocial aspectszUnited States. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : Multicultural Education. 4aEducation : Social Context of Education. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aEDUCATION / Essays.2bisacsh1 aBriscoe, Felecia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriscoe, Felecia M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChoti, Damaris Moraa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl-Amin, Aisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiles, Mark S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffin-EL